          "body": "The psalm's argument is not sentimental but logical: if God is who He is, praise is the only coherent response. The argument runs in three steps. First, God's nature demands it — He is Elyon (Most High), Yehovah (covenant LORD), and melekh gadol (great King) over all the earth; any power that does not honor Him misunderstands its own position (v.2). Second, God's acts confirm it — He has subdued nations, chosen His people's inheritance, and ascended to His throne; history itself is the evidence of His reign (vv. 3-5). Third, God's future makes it certain — the nations' rulers will assemble as His people; the consummation of the covenant is sure (v.9). The psalm asks worshippers not to manufacture praise out of emotional experience but to look at the facts — God's character, God's history, God's trajectory — and respond accordingly. This is what Psalms scholars call doxology as declaration: praise is the mind's acknowledgment of reality, not the heart's production of feeling."
