      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "Sing praises with understanding — worship as theological act",
        "range": "47:6-7",
        "excerpt": "Sing praises to God, sing praises; sing praises to our King, sing praises. For God is the King of all the earth; sing praises with a skillful psalm.",
        "body": "The psalm's second stanza opens with the most concentrated imperative cluster in any enthronement psalm: the verb *zamar* (sing praises, make music) appears five times in two verses. The repetition is not literary accident or filler; it is the rhetorical equivalent of sustained applause — the congregation's response to the enthronement just proclaimed keeps erupting before a new sentence can form. John Calvin comments on this cascade: 'The prophet commands them again and again to sing, because we are so cold and careless in the praises of God, that we need to be repeatedly urged.'\n\nBut verse 7's closing phrase stops the cascade with a qualification: 'sing praises with a skillful psalm' — the Hebrew *maskil*, often translated 'with understanding' or 'with insight.' The word *maskil* appears in the superscriptions of thirteen psalms and carries the sense of instructed, contemplative, theologically deliberate praise. This is not the prohibition of exuberant worship; it is the requirement that exuberance be attached to truth. The cascade of zamar is right; but it must be *zamar maskil* — music shaped by understanding, praise that knows what it is celebrating. Howard Hendricks observed that emotionalism without content is enthusiasm without traction. The psalm commands both: feel the full weight of the five imperatives, and know the theology that grounds them.\n\nThe rationale for the second stanza's imperative is structurally parallel to the first: 'For God is the King of all the earth' (v.7) mirrors 'For the Lord Most High is to be feared, a great King over all the earth' (v.2). The psalm is not simply repeating itself — it is widening the scope. In verse 2, God is *a* great King over all the earth, described as Yehovah in covenant relation to Israel. In verse 7, God is *the* King of all the earth — the definite article carries the exclusive claim. There is no other King of all the earth. Every other king is a regional official of a sovereign who rules the whole.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Zamar* (sing praises) is the root of *mizmor* (psalm, as in the superscription) — the five imperatives in vv.6-7 are all derived from the same root as the word for the psalm-genre itself. *Maskil* — from *sakal*, to have insight, to act wisely — carries the double sense of skillful and theologically understanding. The combination suggests liturgical excellence married to doctrinal clarity."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "God reigns and the nations gather — the eschatological consummation",
        "range": "47:8-9",
        "excerpt": "God reigns over the nations, God sits on His holy throne. The princes of the people have assembled themselves as the people of the God of Abraham.",
        "body": "The psalm reaches its climax in a declaration (v.8) and a vision (v.9). The declaration is as compressed and absolute as any theological statement in the Psalter: 'God reigns over the nations, God sits on His holy throne.' The double subject (*Elohim... Elohim*) and the double predicate (reigns... sits) create a parallelism of governance and stability. 'Reigns' (*malakh*) is the active exercise of royal authority — present and ongoing. 'Sits on His holy throne' is the settled, established position of transcendent sovereignty. The God who ascended (v.5) has arrived; the God who ascended now sits. His kingship is not precarious or contested; it is seated.\n\nThe phrase 'His holy throne' locates that authority in the realm of divine holiness — above the thrones of Assyria, Babylon, Persia, Rome, or any modern superpower. This is the same throne described in Isaiah 6:1 ('I saw the Lord sitting on a throne, lofty and exalted') and Revelation 4:2 ('a throne was standing in heaven, and One sitting on the throne'). The throne is not in any earthly capital; no military campaign can unseat its Occupant; no election can remove Him.\n\nVerse 9 is the psalm's eschatological summit and its most theologically radical statement. The nobles (*nadiv*) of the nations — not the lowly, not the dispossessed, but the ruling powers who hold 'the shields of the earth' — have assembled (*asaph*, perfect tense) as 'the people of the God of Abraham.' Three things are remarkable here. First, the ruling class is gathered — the psalm's vision of God's ultimate sovereignty extends not only to the poor who have no choice but to the powerful who do. Second, they are gathered 'as' the people of the God of Abraham — they have taken on Israelite identity, becoming co-members of the covenant community. Third, this is spoken in the perfect tense — the psalmist, in prophetic anticipation, speaks of the eschatological gathering as already accomplished.\n\nThe theological payoff is enormous. Abraham was told that 'in you all the families of the earth will be blessed' (Genesis 12:3). Psalm 47 envisions that promise reaching its consummation: rulers from every nation streaming into the covenant people of Abraham's God. The New Testament takes this exactly literally: in Christ, 'there is neither Jew nor Greek' (Galatians 3:28), Gentiles are 'fellow citizens with the saints, and are of God's household' (Ephesians 2:19), and the Revelation shows 'a great multitude which no one could count, from every nation and all tribes and peoples and tongues, standing before the throne' (Revelation 7:9). The psalm does not contradict the New Testament's Gentile mission; it demands it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Malakh* (reigns, v.8) is the denominative verb from *melekh* (king) — God does not merely hold the title; He exercises it. *Nadiv* (nobles, princes) — those who give freely, who lead voluntarily — is a word of nobility and generosity, not mere military power. *Magen* (shields) = the shields of the earth's military rulers, a synecdoche for political-military sovereignty: even that belongs to God. *Am avraham* (people of Abraham) — the assembled nations take on the identity of the covenant family."
      }
